Q551: Grade 12, Math Final Exam. 3 days had left and I had come to the realization I didn't know anything and for the first time in my life, I might just fail in a class. It was mainly because I relied on a tutor to teach me as my school didn't let me attend math class as I opted for Computer Science instead and I could only have one or the other. I realized by relying on a 3rd person I become vulnerable. It was the worst feeling of my life! And I just wanted it to end. Over the next few hours, I tried studying but then simply gave up thinking does it even matter anymore. But somehow I pulled together some motivation about how if I don't pass this course UofT will revoke its offer of admission. I got to work and didn't even sleep the night before the final. I gave up studying around 4 hours before the final knowing I had only learned enough to help me pass and not succeed at this class. And I don't want to experience that or put my self through those emotions ever again.
Q552: Trying to pull myself together and focusing on what matters. And realizing that it is never too late to do some damage control.
Q553: I think things haven't been the same since that night. Something has changed and not for the better. And I must take the control back and change myself.
Q554: My courses, Coming to UofT, Post applications. It's just been all too much and too fast. Adjusting to the way things are taught at UofT has been pretty rough as well. I sometimes feel like professors don't care and the TA's as well. There is no student-teacher connection between a prof and student here. It is like you're left high and dry on your own to figure everything out. And sometimes I wonder why do I pay a ridiculous amount of money just to listen to some person say things I already know or can find from a quick google search. There is no experiential learning so far. There is no connection between the students and the course. It just all about textbook learning and giving exams. I feel like in the next four years I am gonna walk out of UofT financially drained, with a degree in my hand who's per sq foot price is higher than that of an apartment in downtown Manhattan - while learned almost nothing. This is my biggest troubled thought right now. I don't want this to be a reality for me.

Q561: My younger brother has been an international student at U of T for 12 years and has been unable to complete his degree. This situation has become entangled with his deteriorating mental health. It is very painful to watch him suffer through mental health problems and not be able to help.
Q563: Not being able to help him.
Q565: I did the best I could do to help him. But life is chaotic and random sometimes. You cannot control every event and outcome. I'm trying to learn to let go of the need to control this particular outcome (i.e. my brother's well-being), but it's sometimes not possible because he is my brother and he is fighting to stay alive. It is painful to watch. So I do need to support him through his struggles; it's just that I need to avoid being emotional about it.
Q567: Thinking about the worst possible outcome that might happen in the future.
Q569: It makes me feel hopeless sometimes.
Q571: I have learned to avoid taking actions when I am in an emotional state. I end up avoiding my brother and/or not asking him about his mental health. Another way of looking at it is that I am giving him the space that he needs.
Q573:
Trigger: There is no trigger as such.
Thought: Thinking about my brother's mental health and life struggles.
Feeling: Distracted, feeling anxious sometimes, and demotivated.
Behaviour: I have learned to avoid interacting with my brother when I am in an emotional state. However, when I get stressed about this, it does affect my relationships with other people as well as with my own productivity. I need to learn breathing techniques or other exercises that can help clear the mind.
Q575: Yes, it does in my case because of the gravity of the situation. I do think my response is measured and usually appropriate. It is understandable that my brother's severe struggles with mental health will have an impact on my productivity and my levels of stress.
Q577: This is a difficult question. Hard to say. Sometimes I talk to my other siblings about the problem and it helps to share in the burden of the difficult situation. But there are times when I avoid talking about it, because of the fear of triggering other people's stress levels. Perhaps I need explore this further. I am not sure what an alternative line of thinking would entail when dealing with a sibling who is suffering from mental health problems.
Q500: I don't think it affected my stress levels too much, because the situation is still lingering and has not been resolved.
Q501: The part about reframing our problem in the form of "Trigger:, Emotions:..." etc. was very useful.
Q502: Yes, definitely. It helps to analyze my feelings better.
Q503_4: I think such an activity becomes very useful during a stressful episode as well as during a calm episode to reflect.
Q503_5: It makes one more self-conscious and aware of feelings and behaviors.
Q503_6: This would be unhelpful in the current format. Perhaps in a mobile phone app it would be more helpful. So if we're feeling stressed, we can just pull out our app and answer these questions about what we're going through in the moment, as we're going through it.
Q503_7: If a person does not have confidence in their ability to write, or is not able to express themselves in writing very well, that might lead to more stress. Some people prefer speaking rather than writing.
Q504: I think writing out thoughts has a different effect than speaking with someone. I would be more likely to filter my thoughts and censure myself when talking to someone. Writing, even if it is anonymous, has a bigger effect for me I think.
Q505: Yes, Following a systematic process can make one more self-conscious about the things that trigger them, the emotions they go through, and the effect it has on their behaviour, etc.
Q506: To write down how a situation is affecting us in the format of "Trigger:, etc." I thought that question was very useful.
Q507: I think the rating is a little tricky, because my level of stress with this particular situation varies as the circumstances change. Currently I rated myself a 6, but there are times when it is 2 and other times when it is 8.
Q508: The part about re-framing our problem in the form of "Trigger:, Emotions:..." etc. was very useful. It helped me breakdown how a situation might be affecting me in ways that I hadn't thought about before.
Q509: I don't recall any questions being unhelpful.
Q510:
Frankly, I am not sure. I would have to think about this more.
Perhaps a short quiz on the format of "Trigger:, Emotions;, Behaviour:, etc" model would be help so that we could recall it better later.
Q511: Stay active and engaged in life. Have a variety of interests. Talk to family and friends about more intimate subjects rather than about the latest celebrity gossip.
Q531:
I think this particular question can be made more clear. Approach to be taken towards what?
Making available for us a short PDF guide on how to manage stress would be useful. If it involves us writing out our thoughts, perhaps the writing prompts that were on this survey can also be included as part of the PDF.
(Perhaps it may come later in this survey, but apart from us answering questions, maybe some suggestions on how we can manage stress would be useful).
